{
    "analysis": "None",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load the four telemetry files (metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, error_logs.csv) and produce a compact summary for each file. For each file, return: 1) total row count, 2) min(timestamp) and max(timestamp), 3) list of distinct cmdb_id values (up to top 20), and 4) list of distinct KPI/trace/log names (fields: kpi_name for metric.csv, trace_name for trace.csv, log_name for log.csv) up to top 50. For error_logs.csv, instead of KPI names return up to 20 distinct message samples. Keep outputs compact (no full tables)." }

{
    "analysis": "The Executor's previous run produced a compact summary of all telemetry files. From that result we know: metric.csv (152,352 rows, 59 distinct cmdb_id, 1,292 distinct kpi_name) and covers the target interval 2022-03-21 21:30–21:59 (+0800). trace.csv and log.csv similarly cover the interval; error_logs.csv contains 743 rows and messages only from frontend-0/1/2. With large numbers of component-KPI combinations, the next step is to compute global thresholds to enable anomaly detection. According to the diagnosis workflow, we must calculate global thresholds (e.g., P95) for each component-KPI time series before filtering to the incident window. Therefore we should start by computing P95 for all (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs in metric.csv so we can later detect anomalies within the target time window.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, compute the global P95 (95th percentile) for each component-KPI time series grouped by (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full available series in the file. For each group also return the count of points and the mean value. Return only the top 20 groups sorted by P95 descending, and for each row include: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count, mean, P95. Keep output compact (max 20 rows)." 
}

{
    "analysis": "The metric analysis found many component-KPI series at-or-above their global P95 for the entire 30-minute window. Most anomalies start at 2022-03-21 21:30:00 +0800. Top metric candidates include node-2 (system.udp.connect.num), productcatalogservice2-0 (file descriptors), and many adservice JVM/runtime KPIs. Because multiple components (nodes, containers, services) show persistent anomalies, we cannot pick the root cause component yet. Per the workflow, we must next run trace analysis to (1) determine which service/container is the most downstream faulty component in call chains and (2) check whether there are two distinct failure events affecting different services/times within the same window. To do that we need global thresholds for trace features first, so compute global P95 for trace series and inspect the top trace series by P95 to narrow candidates and durations.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv, compute the global P95 (95th percentile) for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) time series using the full available series in the file. For each group also return the count of points and the mean value. Return the top 20 groups sorted by P95 descending. For each row include: cmdb_id, trace_name, count, mean, P95. Keep output compact (max 20 rows)."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous steps produced global P95 for metric series and identified many metric anomalies during the entire 21:30–21:59 window. Trace-level summary (global P95) shows frontends have the highest trace P95 (trace.self.row_count), and frontends → productcatalogservice traces are also high. Error logs were limited to frontend pods. We still cannot attribute two distinct failures to specific components. Per the diagnosis workflow, the next step is trace-level anomaly detection inside the incident window (using globally computed thresholds). Trace anomalies will help identify which (faulty) services/containers are downstream in call chains and whether there are two separate failure events in time.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Compute global thresholds (P95 and P5) for every (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full trace.csv. Then, filter trace.csv to the incident window 2022-03-21 21:30:00 → 2022-03-21 21:59:00 (UTC+8). For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) within the window compute: window_count, anomaly_count_high (value >= P95), anomaly_count_low (value <= P5), first_anomaly_high_ts (min timestamp of high anomalies or null), first_anomaly_low_ts (min timestamp of low anomalies or null), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, severity_high = (max_value_in_window - P95)/P95 (if P95>0 else null), severity_low = (P5 - min_value_in_window)/P5 (if P5>0 else null). Return groups with anomaly_count_high>0 or anomaly_count_low>0, sorted by (anomaly_count_high+anomaly_count_low) desc then max(severity_high, severity_low) desc, limit to top 20 rows. For each row return: cmdb_id, trace_name, window_count, anomaly_count_high, anomaly_count_low, first_anomaly_high_ts, first_anomaly_low_ts, p95, p5, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, severity_high, severity_low. Keep output compact (max 20 rows)."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis returned many trace series that are constant or have zero/degenerate thresholds (P95 == P5 or P95==0), and all anomalous points start at 2022-03-21 21:30:00 +0800. Metrics show many series at-or-above P95 for the entire 30‑minute window, with top metric candidates including node-2 (system.udp.connect.num), productcatalogservice2-0 (file descriptors), and numerous adservice JVM/runtime KPIs. Because metric and trace anomalies are persistent and often equal to their thresholds (low dynamic range), they do not by themselves pinpoint which component(s) triggered two separate failures. The error_logs summary earlier showed messages only from frontend-0/1/2 — examining error_logs for temporal clustering and message content is the next logical step to identify distinct failure events and candidate root components. I will therefore inspect error_logs.csv for counts by timestamp and by cmdb_id, and sample messages to locate two failure moments and their associated components/messages.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From error_logs.csv (use full file), restrict to the incident window 2022-03-21 21:30:00 → 2022-03-21 21:59:59 (UTC+8). Produce a compact summary with: 1) top 20 timestamps (sorted by message count desc) showing timestamp, count, and up to 3 distinct cmdb_id involved at that timestamp; 2) for each cmdb_id present in error_logs, show total message count in window, earliest message timestamp, latest message timestamp; 3) up to 10 distinct sample messages across the file (shortened to 200 characters each). Limit returned rows per table as specified." }

{
    "analysis": "From previous steps we have: 1) metric analysis found many series at-or-above their global P95 for the entire 21:30–21:59 window (notable candidates: node-2 system.udp.connect.num, productcatalogservice2-0 file_descriptors, and many adservice JVM/runtime KPIs). 2) Trace analysis showed frontends dominate trace volumes and many trace metrics are degenerate (P95≈P5), so trace anomalies were uninformative. 3) error_logs are concentrated on frontend pods (frontend-2:334 msgs, frontend-1:272, frontend-0:137) with messages spanning the whole window and repeated small clusters (top timestamps with 2–3 messages across frontends). Overall, many metrics/traces are persistently high or constant across the entire window, and error logs point to frontend pods being symptomatic. We still cannot identify two distinct failure root causes/timestamps. To localize distinct failure events and candidate root components, the next logical step is to analyze aggregated normalized logs (log.csv) using global thresholds (P95) to detect significant spikes in log.error_count or row_count within the window and extract earliest anomaly timestamps and severities per component. This will help find the two failure occurrence times and which components first showed abnormal log behavior.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using log.csv: 1) compute global P95 for each (cmdb_id, log_name) over the full file series; 2) filter log.csv to the incident window 2022-03-21 21:30:00 → 2022-03-21 21:59:00 (UTC+8); 3) for each (cmdb_id, log_name) group in the window compute: window_count, anomaly_count (value >= global P95), first_anomaly_ts (min timestamp of anomaly points), max_value_in_window, and severity = (max_value_in_window - P95)/P95 (if P95>0 else null); 4) return groups with anomaly_count>0 sorted by first_anomaly_ts ascending then severity descending, limited to top 20 rows; include fields: cmdb_id, log_name, window_count, anomaly_count, first_anomaly_ts, P95, max_value_in_window, severity. Keep output compact (max 20 rows)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have processed global thresholds and detected persistent anomalies across metrics and traces for the entire 21:30–21:59 window. Metric anomalies: many series are at-or-above P95 throughout the window (notable: node-2.system.udp.connect.num starting 21:30 with highest relative severity; productcatalogservice2-0 file_descriptors; many adservice JVM metrics). Trace anomalies were largely degenerate (P95≈P5) and unhelpful. error_logs are concentrated on frontend pods (frontend-2:334, frontend-1:272, frontend-0:137) with many short second-level clusters (top timestamps showing 2–3 messages across frontends) scattered through the window. log.csv anomalies (log.row_count, log.error_count) show many services with elevated row_count starting at 21:30 and numerous log.error_count groups with P95==0 (undefined severity). Overall: symptoms point toward frontend pods showing error messages throughout the window, and many service/container metrics are anomalous from the very start of the window (21:30). We still do not have two distinct failure occurrence times clearly identified. To detect whether there are two distinct failures and to find their exact occurrence times, we should aggregate error_logs at minute granularity (floor timestamps to minute) to detect minute-level peaks (two peaks would indicate two failure events). This will also show which frontend(s) contributed to each peak so we can select candidate root components for each event.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From error_logs.csv, restrict to 2022-03-21 21:30:00 → 2022-03-21 21:59:59 (UTC+8). Aggregate logs by minute (floor timestamps to minute). For each minute return: minute_timestamp, total_message_count, count_frontend-0, count_frontend-1, count_frontend-2, and a sample up-to-3 distinct message snippets seen in that minute. Return the top 10 minutes sorted by total_message_count desc then minute_timestamp asc. Keep output compact (max 10 rows)." }

{
    "analysis": "The minute-aggregated error_logs show concentrated error bursts affecting all three frontend pods, with the highest volumes clustered in the early window (peaks around 21:30–21:36) and another notable peak at 21:45. Metrics and traces earlier showed many series persistently at-or-above P95 from 21:30 onward, so metrics alone point to widespread persistent anomalies starting at the window start (21:30). To pin down two distinct failure occurrences and the root cause component for each, we need to find when metric series first crossed their global thresholds (first_anomaly_ts) and whether there is a secondary wave of first-time anomalies around 21:45 that corresponds to the second failure peak seen in error logs. Aggregating the first_anomaly timestamps from metrics to minute granularity will reveal minutes when many components first became anomalous — these minutes are strong candidates for root-cause occurrence times. Next, we should retrieve which components first became anomalous at the top minute candidates so we can inspect their resource KPIs/traces/logs to decide root cause component and reason for each failure.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv and the previously computed global P95 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name):\n1) Filter metric.csv to the incident window 2022-03-21 21:30:00 → 2022-03-21 21:59:00 (UTC+8).\n2) For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name), find the earliest timestamp in the window where value >= global P95 (first_anomaly_ts). If a series has no such point in the window, ignore it.\n3) Aggregate these first_anomaly_ts by minute (floor to minute) and compute: minute_timestamp, count_of_series_starting_that_minute, and up to 5 distinct sample cmdb_id values whose series first crossed P95 at that minute.\n4) Return the top 10 minutes sorted by count_of_series_starting_that_minute desc then minute_timestamp asc. For each row return: minute_timestamp, count_of_series_starting_that_minute, sample_cmdb_ids (up to 5). Keep output compact (max 10 rows)."
}

{
    "analysis": "The Executor returned network-focused metric results showing a massive, simultaneous onset at 2022-03-21 21:30:00 +0800. The largest relative deviations (severity) at the onset are container-level network_receive_MB spikes on many backend containers (examples: adservice-1, checkoutservice-2, cartservice-2, cartservice-1, adservice2-0, currencyservice-0). Node-level I/O await/w_await also show strong deviations but generally with lower relative severity than the top container network_receive spikes. Error logs are concentrated on frontend pods with minute-level peaks around 21:30–21:36 and another peak near 21:45. Metric first-crossing aggregation shows a massive bulk of series (3,655) first crossing P95 at exactly 21:30:00 +0800, and smaller waves later (e.g., 21:43, 21:45, 21:58).

What this implies: the initial failure (strong onset) began at 21:30:00 +0800 and is characterized by extreme relative increases in container-level network receive (many backend containers) and elevated node I/O latency. According to the diagnosis rules, when faults appear at multiple levels we should pick the level with the largest deviation to determine the root-cause level — here the largest deviations are at container network receive (container-level). To pick the exact root-cause container among several container-level candidates, we must use traces and logs to identify which of these faulty containers is the most downstream faulty component in call chains (i.e., the last faulty service in traces) or which is most directly correlated with frontend symptoms. We therefore need targeted trace analysis for the top network-receive candidate containers to see whether they are appearing as downstream services receiving requests from frontends and whether their trace KPIs (duration, row_count, error_rate) also show anomalies at 21:30. This will let us pick the most likely root-cause container for the first failure.

We have not yet identified the second failure occurrence definitively (candidates include ~21:43/21:45 and 21:58). After localizing the root cause of the initial 21:30 event, we will repeat similar steps focused on the later peak(s) to find the second failure component/time/reason.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv and the previously computed global thresholds for traces: For the following candidate cmdb_id list [adservice-1, checkoutservice-2, cartservice-2, cartservice-1, adservice2-0, currencyservice-0, frontend-2, frontend-1, frontend-0], find trace series that represent incoming calls from frontends or show they receive traffic (trace_name containing 'from_frontend' OR 'to_' followed by the service name OR trace.self.* metrics). For each matching (cmdb_id, trace_name) group, restrict to the incident window 2022-03-21 21:30:00 → 2022-03-21 21:59:00 (UTC+8) and compute: window_count, anomaly_count_high (value >= trace global P95), first_anomaly_high_ts (min ts of such points or null), max_value_in_window, and severity_high = (max_value_in_window - P95)/P95 (if P95>0 else null). Return only groups with anomaly_count_high>0, sorted by first_anomaly_high_ts asc then severity_high desc, limit to top 30 rows. For each row return: cmdb_id, trace_name, window_count, anomaly_count_high, first_anomaly_high_ts, p95, max_value_in_window, severity_high. Keep output compact." }

